title: parse-diagnostics Operator
type: text/vnd.tiddlywiki

<<.from-version "5.5.0">> A parser records a <<.def "diagnostic">> whenever it recovers from source it cannot fully make sense of: an emphasis delimiter that never closes, a fenced block that runs to the end of the tiddler, a definition missing its `\end`. The tiddler still renders, and the diagnostic explains what the parser did about it.

Each diagnostic carries a range, a severity, a code, a source and a message. The severities run `error`, `warning`, `info` and `hint`, worst first.

! Suffixes

|!Suffix |!Output |
|(none) |the input titles that carry a diagnostic |
|`grade` |the worst severity each input title carries, or `clean` |
|`count` |how many diagnostics each input title carries |
|`codes` |the distinct diagnostic codes across the input titles |

! Examples

<<.operator-example 1 "[all[tiddlers]parse-diagnostics[]]" "the tiddlers the parser could not fully read">>
<<.operator-example 2 "[all[tiddlers]!parse-diagnostics[]]" "the tiddlers that parse cleanly">>
<<.operator-example 3 "[all[tiddlers]parse-diagnostics:codes[]]" "the faults present in this wiki">>
<<.operator-example 4 "[all[tiddlers]parse-diagnostics:grade[]]" "the worst severity each tiddler carries">>

! Any grammar

The operator reads the diagnostics from the parse result rather than from the wikitext parser, so a plugin that registers a parser for its own content type populates the same array and grades on the same scale. See ParserDiagnostics.
